This premise states that for all but finitely many `i` in the `IsDedekindDomain.HeightOneSpectrum` (which are the primes for the restricted product), the map `(fun v ↦ (ContinuousLinearEquiv.toContinuousAddEquiv (@Aux.continuousBaseChange V _ _ _ _ φ)).1 i)` is a bijection on the specified sets.

To prove this, we need to show that for any `i` (representing a prime `p`), the map `(fun v ↦ (ContinuousLinearEquiv.toContinuousAddEquiv (@Aux.continuousBaseChange V _ _ _ _ φ)).1 i)` is a bijection. This map is `(c_v i).1`, which is `(c_v i).toEquiv`.

Let `Equiv_c_v_i := (c_v i).toEquiv`. We need to show `Set.BijOn Equiv_c_v_i (Set.range _) (Set.range _)`.

`Equiv_c_v_i` is defined as `(c_v i).toEquiv = (c_v i).toEquiv`. Let's look at the definition of `c_v`:
`noncomputable def c_v (v : IsDedekindDomain.HeightOneSpectrum (𝓞 ℚ)) : IntegralLattice ℤ ℚ V ⊗[ℤ] v.adicCompletion ℚ ≃L[v.adicCompletion ℚ] V ⊗[ℚ] v.adicCompletion ℚ := ...`

The `toEquiv` of this `c_v` is `(fun v ↦ (c_v i).toEquiv v)`, which is the identity map on `V`. So, we need to show that the identity map is a bijection on the sets `↑((↑(@Aux.c_v_alg V _ _ i)).toAddMonoidHom.comp ...).range` for all but finitely many `i`. This is true because the identity map is always a bijection.

The fix would be to replace the `sorry` with a proof of this fact. This can be done by showing that the map is the identity, and the identity is a bijection.

